<br>
The only thing that drops for the entire party are QUEST items, and only if every person in the party has triggered the quest and does everything for the quest up to the point.  This was done to foster cooperation, remove competition, and stop camp lists for quest mobs.<br>
<br>
There are no mob/creature ratios for dropped items like a FBSS.  All of those tables are randomized, as is looting, so everything in that regard is take care of.  If you kill a creature that drops a neat item as loot, then it is randomly distributed to someone when it is looted, so only one person gets it.  What they do with it is their business.  This is done with all loot that is DROPPED, but that is completely different than what you are referring to.<br>
<br>
What you are referring to are quest items.  Let me give you an example:<br>
<br>
I go to a keep and talk to an NPC that gives me a quest.  It says I must go to a graveyard and kill a creature to rid the town of his presence.  I show up at the graveyard and don't see the creature, but there is another person there.  I ask them if they've seen this creature, and they say they have not, but they too are looking for him.  A third person is there as well, but they are fighting and have never heard of this creature or the quest.  We send him off to talk to the NPC, but he cannot get the quest because he is still too young.  He decides to stay anyway, just to see what happens.  The three of us decide to group together and kill other creatures as we wait.  The wait isn't long and the creature appears.  We kill it.  <br>
<br>
I get a magic belt, as does the first person I spoke to.  The belts dropped directly into our inventories, it wasn't looted.  But the third person didn't get the belt, because he had not started the quest.   The creature also DROPPED some tattered chain gloves.  When someone loots the item, it falls into my inventory.  But I cannot wear the gloves and the third person can.  I give the third person the gloves (though I could have sold them) because he can wear them and in appreciation for his unselfishly helping us out.  (ps, this actually happened.  It is a very low level quest for a +1 or +2 belt in Albion)<br>
<br>
Now... the only auto-drop item that is 'given' to everyone is a quest item.  Not all auto-drop items are the actual end loot itelf.  In fact, it is usually just a component for a quest, and you have to return the item to actually complete the quest.<br>
<br>
